# CODING STANDARDS (GENERAL)

## Purpose
- Keep changes safe, readable, and easy to verify.
- Favor small, testable updates over broad rewrites.

## Core Standards
- Solve the requested outcome with the smallest reasonable change.
- Match existing project patterns before introducing new abstractions.
- Prefer clear naming and straightforward control flow.
- Add comments only where intent is non-obvious.

## Safety Guardrails
- Do not revert unrelated local changes.
- Avoid destructive operations unless explicitly approved.
- Confirm assumptions with evidence from the codebase before acting.
- If requirements conflict, pause and ask for clarification.

## Quality Checks
- After substantive edits, run the project's lint/type checks when available.
- Fix issues introduced by the change before considering task complete.
- Call out any remaining risks or unverified paths.

## Git Hygiene
- Do not create commits unless explicitly requested.
- When committing, keep messages clear about intent and outcome.
- Do not push unless explicitly requested.

## Reuse Notes
- Keep this rule always-on for active projects.
- Add project-specific constraints in separate rules so this file stays reusable.
